{
  "card_id": "inversion_fair_value_gap",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Inversion Fair Value Gap",
  "aliases": [
    "Fair Value Gap Inversion",
    "ifvg",
    "IFVG",
    "inversion",
    "inversion fvg",
    "Inversion FVG"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A Fair Value Gap (bullish BISI or bearish SIBI) that price closes through, inverting its role. The former gap then acts as support (when a bearish gap is closed above) or resistance (when a bullish gap is closed below). The inversion is confirmed only after a full-body candle close completely outside the gap's extreme boundary.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a standard Fair Value Gap (three-candle pattern where first candle low and third candle high do not overlap, or vice versa).",
    "For a bullish Fair Value Gap (BISI), a candle close below the entire gap confirms an inversion, turning it into resistance.",
    "For a bearish Fair Value Gap (SIBI), a candle close above the entire gap confirms an inversion, turning it into support.",
    "A close beyond the consequent encroachment (50% of the gap) without closing beyond the full gap is an early signal, but full inversion requires a close completely outside the gap.",
    "The inverted gap is only valid after a full-body candle close outside its extreme boundary.",
    "After confirmation, mark the original FVG area as an Inversion Fair Value Gap with reversed polarity.",
    "Wait for price to retest the IFVG area, focusing on reaction near the Consequent Encroachment (50% level).",
    "If price closes through the IFVG area again (second crossing), the IFVG becomes invalid.",
    "In a reversal sequence (TTRS), IFVG must occur after Turtle Soup (liquidity sweep) for confirmation.",
    "In the AMD framework, wait for the manipulation phase to complete (price sweeps liquidity and aggressively returns to range) before retesting IFVG.",
    "When other PD Arrays (e.g., Order Block Mean Threshold) align with the IFVG area, it provides additional confirmation."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Inverted Fair Value Gaps act as support (formerly bearish SIBI) or resistance (formerly bullish BISI) on retests. Traders may enter at the consequent encroachment for a tighter stop, or at the full retest, anticipating continuation. Entries are often combined with liquidity sweeps to target opposite side liquidity. Stop loss placed beyond the swing high/low on the opposite side of IFVG. Targets aim for buy-side or sell-side liquidity. In AMD framework, used after manipulation leg. In reversal sequences, serves as second confirmation step. Can be combined with Order Blocks for higher reliability.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering prematurely when price only closes beyond the consequent encroachment but not the full Fair Value Gap.",
    "Taking an entry that does not meet the minimum risk-to-reward requirement (e.g., only 1R) without adjusting entry to the consequent encroachment.",
    "Mistaking a simple retest of a Fair Value Gap for an inversion when price has not closed through it.",
    "Using inversions without context of liquidity sweeps or external-to-internal liquidity cycles.",
    "Considering a price touch or penetration of the FVG without a close through as a reversal signal.",
    "Assuming the FVG reversal must occur immediately after the crossing event, ignoring delayed retests after consolidation.",
    "Continuing to use the FVG as support/resistance in its original direction after it has been crossed.",
    "Relying solely on price touching the Consequent Encroachment (50% level) to confirm IFVG without a full close through the entire FVG.",
    "During IFVG retest, if price closes below the Consequent Encroachment, still expecting the original direction; instead, expect continuation in the crossing direction.",
    "In AMD framework, looking for IFVG entry before the manipulation phase is complete (price has not aggressively returned to range).",
    "Confusing IFVG entry with a break of structure (BOS); IFVG entry does not require a BOS.",
    "Trying to master all reversal sequence concepts (Turtle Soup, IFVG, CISD, Breaker Block, FVG) simultaneously, leading to analysis overload."
  ],
